Rating: 4
This is now part of my personal tested recipe collection. Any cook who reads the coup recipe can tell you that the outcome will depend on two things, the quality of the asparagus and the quality of the chicken stock. I served this at a dinner party on Saturday. In preparation I made my own chicken stock at home on Thursday and made the soup Friday. It kept beautifully in the refrigerator for the Saturday party. This is one of the great joys of serving soup as a hostess, it actually gets better if refrigerated for a couple of days, the flavors blend and develop. I very much prefer a formal first course of really good homemade soup, than the usual greasy and fattening finger foods frequently served as appetizers. Besides using my own homemade chicken stock, I used a slightly different technique with the asparagus. I steamed the asparagus, then pureed it in a food processor, then added it to the chicken stock and leeks in the soup pot. The food processor does such a good job of pureeing the asparagus that I didn't need to strain the soup to remove stray pieces of asparagus stalk. The flans seemed to be a big success with the guests. I followed the recipe exactly except that I left out the pepper since I didn't have any white pepper on hand. I found them creamy smooth with a delightfully subtle cheesy flavor. Note that when I was straining the milk, cheese and cream mixture into the egg mixture, there was alot of hard cheese chunks in the strainer. I ignored them and threw them away as noted in the recipe. Don't let this worry you, the flans turned out great. Although the flans were very tender and fragile, they did reheat quite well in the microwave. I think my guests really liked the soup and flan presentation. If you take advantage of the fact that the soup can be made several days ahead then frozen or stored in an air tight container, the dish is very good for parties. I will definitely make this again.

